\h Esther
\toc1 Esther
\toc2 Esther
\toc3 Est.
\mt1 Esther
\is1 Introduction
\ip This account tells about the life of a young Jewish woman named Esther. These events happened back when King Ahasuerus (more widely known as King Xerxes) ruled over the kingdom of Persia. After Queen Vashti was banished for refusing to dance in front the king's guests at a drinking party, Esther was chosen as the new queen without revealing her Jewish background. But there was a high official called Haman who was offended by Esther's Jewish guardian and in his anger, determined to annihilate all of the Jews from the kingdom. This account reveals how Ether's courage and her love for her Jewish people leads her to help them and eventually helps to save their lives.
\ip The account also reveals the source of a Jewish feast named вҖҳPurimвҖҷ, which to this day is a time when Jewish people celebrate how God saved them from their enemy, Haman.
\iot Main components of this account
\io1 Esther becomes Queen of Persia \ior 1:1вҖ“2:23\ior*
\io1 Haman's threat to the Jews \ior 3:1вҖ“5:14\ior*
\io1 Haman's execution \ior 6:1вҖ“7:10\ior*
\io1 The Jewish people destroy their enemies \ior 8:1вҖ“10:3\ior*
\rem This is still a very early look into the unfinished text of the Open English Translation of the Bible. Please double-check the text in advance before using in public.
\ie
\c 1
\s1 Queen Vashti refuses King Ahasuerus
\rem /s1 King Ahasuerus's banquet; Queen Vashti Deposed; Queen Vashti Defies King Xerxes; King Ahasuerus Deposes Queen Vashti; The King's Banquet
\p
\v 1 The following events happened during the reignВҰ228506 of \add King\add* AhasuerusВҰ228503.\x + \xo 1:1: \xt Ezr 4:6.\x* (\add Also known as King Xerxes,\add* he ruled \add the empire of Persia\add* withВҰ228502 127 provincesВҰ228514 from IndiaВҰ228507 all the way across to EthiopiaВҰ228510.)
\v 2 In thoseВҰ228517 daysВҰ228516, he ruled his empire from \add a city called\add* ShushanВҰ228526,\f + \fr 1:2 \ft Known as вҖҳSusaвҖҷ in many 20th century translations, even though earlier English translations often got it correct.\f* \add Persia's\add* capital.
\p
\v 3 In the third year of his reignВҰ228531, he hosted a celebration for all of his officials and for every important person who worked for him, as well as the officers who served in the army of the \add combined empire\add* of PersiaВҰ228540 and MediaВҰ228541, the wealthy landowners, and the officials of the provincesВҰ228544. The king was presentВҰ228545 in person \add to host the celebration\add*
\v 4 which, over a period of six months, would displayВҰ228547 the incredible wealth and prestige of his empire and his personal wealth and power.
\p
\v 5 ThenВҰ228564 atВҰ228564 the end of that time, the kingВҰ228569 hosted \add another\add* celebration, butВҰ228564 this time for all the peopleВҰ228572 in the royal fort in ShushanВҰ228574, from the nobles to the least prestigious. He held this celebration over an entire week in the enclosed gardenВҰ228584 of the royal palaceВҰ228585.
\v 6 There were white and blue curtains hanging from white and purpleВҰ228596 cordsВҰ228593 attached to silver rings on marble pillarsВҰ228601. The guests reclined on goldВҰ228605 and silver couchesВҰ228603 set on a mosaic floor that was made of red and white marble, and mother-of-pearlВҰ228612 and other expensive stonesВҰ228613.
\v 7 Drinks were servedВҰ228615 inВҰ228616 golden goblets, andВҰ228621 each one was a unique design. The king'sВҰ228625 wine seemed limitless as he displayed his generosity,
\v 8 andВҰ228646 it was served accordingВҰ228628 to his rule: ThereВҰ228631 is no compulsion to drinkВҰ228627, butВҰ228627 all of his servants were to give each guest however much they wanted.
\p
\v 9 Meanwhile, Queen VashtiВҰ228649 was hosting a celebration for the womenВҰ228653 \add in a different part\add* of the king's royalВҰ228655 palace.
\rem /s1 Queen Vashti Deposed
\p
\v 10 On the seventh dayВҰ228661 of the celebrations, when the king was feeling cheery from his wine-drinking, he ordered seven of his chief servants (MehumanВҰ228669, BizthaВҰ228670, HarbonaВҰ228671, BigthaВҰ228672, AbagthaВҰ228673, ZetharВҰ228674, and Karkas)
\v 11 to bringВҰ228685 Queen VashtiВҰ228688, wearing her royalВҰ228693 crownВҰ228692, to him inВҰ228692 orderВҰ228694 to show her beautyВҰ228699 to the peopleВҰ228695 and the officialsВҰ228696, because sheВҰ228704 was very attractive.
\v 12 ButВҰ228706 when the servants came and told her the king's commandВҰ228710, Queen VashtiВҰ228708 refusedВҰ228706 to come. WhenВҰ228706 the king found this out, he got very angryВҰ228715 and \add sat there\add* raging.
\v 13 SoВҰ228724 he \add called over\add* his advisors who knew the law and could make good decisions, and discussed with them what he should do.
\v 14 (His closest advisors were Karshena, ShetharВҰ228743, AdmathaВҰ228744, TarshishВҰ228745, MeresВҰ228746, MarsenaВҰ228747, and Memukan. These sevenВҰ228749 officials were from \add various places in the empire\add* of PersiaВҰ228752 and MediaВҰ228753 and they advised the kingВҰ228756 personally, \add thus making them\add* the most powerful officials in the empire.)
\v 15 вҖңAccordingВҰ228761 to \add our\add* law,вҖқ \add the kingВҰ228776 asked,\add* вҖңwhat should be done withВҰ228765 QueenВҰ228773 VashtiВҰ228766, since sheВҰ228772 refused to obey my commandВҰ228775 when the servants passed it onВҰ228765 to her?вҖқ
\p
\v 16 Then Memukan answered the king, \add speaking loudly enough that\add* both the king and his officials could hear. вҖңQueen VashtiВҰ228794 has done wrong,вҖқ he said, вҖңand not only against the king. She has also done wrong against all the officials and peopleВҰ228806 groups in all the provincesВҰ228810 that KingВҰ228786 AhasuerusВҰ228812 \add rules\add*!
\v 17 \add Soon\add* women all over the empire will hear about what the queenВҰ228819 did and they'll say, вҖҳKingВҰ228829 AhasuerusВҰ228830 commanded hisВҰ228837 servants to bringВҰ228832 Queen VashtiВҰ228835 to him, butВҰ228838 she didn'tВҰ228838 go! Then women will stop respecting theirВҰ228826 husbandsВҰ228826.
\v 18 Even today, the leading women of PersiaВҰ228847 and MediaВҰ228849 will hear what the queenВҰ228855 did and start doing the same to \add their husbands who are\add* officialsВҰ228857, and this will cause \add a wave of\add* contemptВҰ228860 and angerВҰ228861.
\v 19 If it pleases you \add to do so\add*, \add your majesty\add*, you should personally issue a royal decree and have it added to the laws of PersiaВҰ228876 and MediaВҰ228878 which cannot be repealed. This decree should say that VashtiВҰ228885 can never again comeВҰ228884 into your presence, and then you should choose a different woman for the royal positionВҰ228889вҖ”someone who's betterВҰ228893 than herВҰ228889.
\v 20 YourВҰ228905 decreeВҰ228897 will be proclaimedВҰ228896 right through your empire, even though it's so hugeВҰ228906, andВҰ228896 thenВҰ228896 all womenВҰ228910, irrespective of their status or position, will honourВҰ228912 their husbandsВҰ228913.
\p
\v 21 This seemed like a good idea to the king andВҰ228919 his officialsВҰ228923, so KingВҰ228922 Ahasuerus followed the adviceВҰ228920 of Memukan
\v 22 and sent letters to every province in his empire. He wrote to every province using its own alphabet and to each peopleВҰ228944 group in its own language. The letters said that men should be the masters over their wives and children, and that a husband should be able to give orders to his wife in his own native language \add that she should understand and obey\add*.
\c 2
\s1 Beautiful Esther enters the king's harem
\rem /s1 Esther becomes queen; Esther Becomes Queen; Esther Made Queen
\p
\v 1 Some time later when KingВҰ228963 AhasuerusВҰ228964 no longer felt so angry, he \add started to miss\add* VashtiВҰ228968. ButВҰ228969 when she'd disobeyed his command, he had made a decree \add thatВҰ228970 she could never come into his presence againВҰ228977\add*.
\v 2 SoВҰ228979 some of the young men who served the king suggested to him, вҖң\add Your majesty, you shouldВҰ228984 get a new wife for yourself.\add* You could tell your servants to look for young virginsВҰ228987 who are very beautiful.
\v 3 You could assign officers in each provinceВҰ228996 of your empire to bring everyВҰ229001 virgin who is very beautiful here to your capital city of ShushanВҰ229010. They could stay in the harem for virgins under the custody of HegaiВҰ229019, the castrated royal guardian who takes care of the young women who live there andВҰ228991 he could arrange for them to receive beauty treatmentsВҰ229025.
\v 4 ThenВҰ229027 you could decide which youngВҰ229027 womanВҰ229027 you like best andВҰ229027 thenВҰ229027 make her queen instead of VashtiВҰ229034.вҖқ
\p The king liked what they suggestedВҰ229036, so he did it.
\p
\v 5 At that time, there was a Jewish man named Mordekai living inВҰ229046 the capital city of ShushanВҰ229046. (He was from the tribe of Benjamin: his father was Jair, his grandfather was ShimeiВҰ229054, and his great-grandfather was KishВҰ229057
\v 6 who'd been taken away from Jerusalem and led to Babylon when KingВҰ229071 NebuchadnezzerВҰ229076 of Babylon had exiled JeconiahВҰ229070, the king of Judah, along with many of his people.)\x + \xo 2:6: \xt 2Ki 24:10-16; 2Ch 36:10.\x*
\v 7 Now Mordekai was taking care of his cousin, who was an orphan. WhenВҰ229080 her fatherВҰ229093 and mother had died, Mordekai had adoptedВҰ229104 her as his own daughterВҰ229087. HerВҰ229102 \add Hebrew\add* name was HadassahВҰ229084, and her \add Persian\add* name was Esther. Esther was now a youngВҰ229095 womanВҰ229095 and she was exceptionally attractive.
\p
\v 8 SoВҰ229109 when the king's command and decree became known, many youngВҰ229116 women were being brought into the capital city of ShushanВҰ229120 and placed under Hegai's charge, and this is what happened to EstherВҰ229127. (Hegai was the overseer of the women.)
\v 9 Hegai was very impressed withВҰ229141 Esther, and he treated her favourablyВҰ229143. He quicklyВҰ229145 arranged for Esther to receive her beautyВҰ229148 treatments and her allotment of food, as well as choosing sevenВҰ229155 female servants from the king's palaceВҰ229161 and assigningВҰ229158 them to be her personal attendants. He also moved Esther and her attendants to the best rooms inВҰ229141 the harem for virgins.
\v 10 (EstherВҰ229174 hadn't revealed her family ties or her Jewishness to anyone, because Mordekai had instructedВҰ229183 her not to.)
\p
\v 11 Every day Mordekai would walkВҰ229195 around inВҰ229209 frontВҰ229196 of the courtyardВҰ229197 of the women'sВҰ229200 harem to find out \add from others\add* how EstherВҰ229205 was doing andВҰ229190 how she was being treated.
\p
\v 12 Each youngВҰ229213 womanВҰ229213 would get twelve months of beautyВҰ229233 treatmentВҰ229233 according to the \add Persian\add* law for womenвҖ”there would be six months of applying oilВҰ229236 of myrrhВҰ229237, thenВҰ229211 six months of perfumesВҰ229240 andВҰ229211 other lotions \add designed for\add* women. ThenВҰ229211 theirВҰ229233 turn would come, one atВҰ229211 a time, to be taken to KingВҰ229219 AhasuerusВҰ229220.
\v 13 TheВҰ229250 young woman was allowed to takeВҰ229257 whatever she wanted from the haremВҰ229259 when she went to the king'sВҰ229264 houseВҰ229263.
\v 14 She'd be taken across in the eveningВҰ229266, and in the morningВҰ229270 she'd be led out to the other harem which was for the concubinesВҰ229285. (That harem was overseen by ShaashgazВҰ229281, another castrated royal guardian.) The womenВҰ229276 taken there wouldn't go againВҰ229289 to the king's houseВҰ229275 unless he had especially liked them and summonedВҰ229299 her back by nameВҰ229300.
\s1 Esther becomes queen
\p
\v 15 Now Esther was the daughter of Mordekai's uncleВҰ229309, AbihailВҰ229308, from whom Mordekai had adopted her as his own daughter. WhenВҰ229302 it was her turn to go to the king, she didn'tВҰ229320 ask for anythingВҰ229322 other than what HegaiВҰ229329, the king's trusted official inВҰ229302 charge of the harem, had advised, andВҰ229302 everyoneВҰ229333 who saw Esther liked her.
\v 16 SoВҰ229344 EstherВҰ229345 was takenВҰ229344 to KingВҰ229348 AhasuerusВҰ229349 atВҰ229354 his royal palace in JanuaryВҰ229359, in the seventhВҰ229362 yearВҰ229360 of his reignВҰ229363,
\v 17 and the kingВҰ229366 lovedВҰ229365 EstherВҰ229369 more than any of the other women. He treated her more kindly and more favourablyВҰ229375 than any of the other young women \add who had become his concubines\add*. He put a royalВҰ229384 crownВҰ229382 onВҰ229385 her head and made her the \add new\add* queenВҰ229386 to replace VashtiВҰ229388.
\v 18 ThenВҰ229390 the kingВҰ229391 hosted a large celebration and invited all his officialsВҰ229396 and servantsВҰ229397 to a feast to celebrate EstherВҰ229400 \add becoming queen\add*. He proclaimed that this would be a time to celebrate for people in all of the provincesВҰ229402 of his empire when they wouldn't have to pay taxes, and he gaveВҰ229404 \add many\add* generous gifts.
\s1 Mordekai and Esther earn the king's favour
\rem /s1 Mordecai Discovers a Plot; Mordecai and Haman; Mordecai Saves the King's Life; Mordecai Uncovers a Conspiracy
\p
\v 19 \add Later onВҰ229409,\add* King Ahasuerus had \add his officers\add* bring more virginsВҰ229410 \add to Shushan\add*. During this time, Mordekai \add had been given a position by the king so\add* he sat \add there\add* atВҰ229409 the king'sВҰ229416 gateВҰ229414.
\v 20 EstherВҰ229419 had still not told anyone that \add she was Jewish\add* because Mordekai had warned herВҰ229421 not to tell anyone. \add What's more,\add* she continued to follow all of Mordekai's instructionsВҰ229426, just as she had done when she was still under his guardianship.
\rem /s1 Mordekai's Loyalty to the King
\p
\v 21 One day when Mordekai was \add onВҰ229445 duty\add* atВҰ229445 the king's gateВҰ229445, two of the king's guardsВҰ229455 who protected the doorway \add to the king's private rooms\add* became angryВҰ229448 withВҰ229445 the king and so they planned to assassinate KingВҰ229447 AhasuerusВҰ229461. (Their names were BigthanВҰ229449 and TereshВҰ229450.)
\v 22 ButВҰ229463 when Mordekai heard what they were planning, he told Queen EstherВҰ229467 about it andВҰ229469 she told the kingВҰ229471, explaining that Mordekai had given her the information.
\v 23 WhenВҰ229475 the matterВҰ229485 was investigatedВҰ229475 and \add the facts\add* discovered, both conspirators were impaled onВҰ229484 \add sharpened wooden\add* poles, and in the presence of the kingВҰ229488, the incident was recorded in the royal record of events.
\c 3
\s1 Haman plans to annihilate the Jews
\rem /s1 Haman's Plot against the Jews; Haman Plots to Destroy the Jews; Haman Undertakes to Destroy the Jews; Haman's Plot to Destroy the Jews
\p
\v 1 Some time later, KingВҰ229496 AhasuerusВҰ229497 promoted Haman, one of his officials (and the son of HammedathaВҰ229503 \add who was a descendant\add* of Agag). The kingВҰ229496 gave Haman a very important positionВҰ229509вҖ”more important than any of his other officials.
\v 2 ThenВҰ229517 the king commandedВҰ229531 that all his other officials had to bow down inВҰ229523 front of Haman to honour him, andВҰ229517 they were doing this atВҰ229523 the king's gateВҰ229523, except for Mordekai who refused to bow down to reverence Haman.
\v 3 вҖңWhyВҰ229552 are youВҰ229550 disobeying the king's commandВҰ229553?вҖқ asked the other royal servantsВҰ229542 atВҰ229546 the king's gateВҰ229546.
\v 4 Mordekai told them that it was because he was a Jew \add (andВҰ229556 Jews only worship Yahweh)\add*. He didn'tВҰ229562 listenВҰ229563 to their \add warnings\add* so they told HamanВҰ229566 about it to seeВҰ229567 if he would tolerateВҰ229568 Mordekai inВҰ229557 keeping refusing to bow down.
\v 5 WhenВҰ229580 Haman sawВҰ229580 that Mordekai would not bow down to him or show him reverence, he was furious.
\v 6 ButВҰ229593 Haman despised the idea of just punishing Mordekai because he'd been told that Mordekai \add didn't bow to him because\add* Mordekai was a Jew. SoВҰ229593 HamanВҰ229609 decided to annihilate all of Mordekai's people, i.e., all the Jews throughout the kingdomВҰ229619 of AhasuerusВҰ229620.
\p
\v 7 In early April of the twelfth year of KingВҰ229633 Ahasuerus' reign, HamanВҰ229640 got his servants to throwВҰ229635 dice \add to select the best month and the best day to kill the Jews\add*, and the 13th of March was chosen.
\p
\v 8 Then HamanВҰ229656 \add went to\add* KingВҰ229657 AhasuerusВҰ229658 and said, вҖң\add Your Majesty,\add* thereВҰ229659 is a certain group of people who live amongВҰ229665 the other peoples in every provinceВҰ229668 of your empire. They have theirВҰ229670 own set of laws, so they don'tВҰ229682 obey your laws. It's not good for you to allow them to continue to live in your empire.
\v 9 Your majesty, if you approve of this plan, then write a decree saying that all of the Jews must be destroyedВҰ229694. \add When they're dead, we can take all of theirВҰ229694 possessions, andВҰ229695 from that\add* I will give 300 tons of silverВҰ229699 to your administrators for them to put into your royal treasuriesВҰ229709.вҖқ
\p
\v 10 \add This seemed sensible to\add* the king so he removed his signet ring from his finger andВҰ229712 he gaveВҰ229719 it\f + \fr 3:10 \ft Having the king's signet ring enabled Haman to stamp the king's seal (like a signature) onto the newly drafted laws.\f* to Haman (the son of HammedathaВҰ229723, the AgagiteВҰ229724, the adversary of the Jews).
\v 11 The kingВҰ229729 told HamanВҰ229730, вҖңYou can keep the moneyВҰ229731 for yourself, andВҰ229728 you can do whatever you want to do withВҰ229738 those peopleВҰ229734.вҖқ
\p
\v 12 On the thirteenth dayВҰ229747 of that same monthВҰ229743, Haman called in the royal scribes, and he dictated a letter to them. He told them to send copies to the royal officialsВҰ229771, the governorsВҰ229762 of each province, and the leaders of each people group \add within the empire\add*. The scribes translated the letter so it could be sent to each province using its own alphabet and to each people group in its own languageВҰ229779. To show that he was sending the letter under the king's own authority, Haman sealedВҰ229784 each copy of the letter withВҰ229743 the ring that had the king's official seal onВҰ229743 it.
\v 13 Couriers delivered the letters to the officials in every provinceВҰ229796 in the empire. The letters said to completely destroyВҰ229798 all the Jews, including the children andВҰ229788 womenВҰ229811, onВҰ229790 a single day. That was to be the thirteenth day of March early in the following year. The letters also stated that those who killed the Jews could take everything that belonged to them.
\v 14 The letter told the officials to displayВҰ229835 copies where everyone could see themвҖ”that way all the peopleВҰ229838 in every single provinceВҰ229833 would know that the king had commanded this, andВҰ229834 they could get readyВҰ229840 for when the dayВҰ229841 came.
\p
\v 15 So couriersВҰ229844 hurriedВҰ229846 off withВҰ229847 the letters as the king had commandedВҰ229847. A herald in the capital cityВҰ229857 of Shushan also proclaimed what the letters said. Then the king and HamanВҰ229854 relaxed and drank together, butВҰ229849 there was \add total\add* confusionВҰ229859 in Shushan \add about how all of this would work out\add*.
\c 4
\s1 Mordekai asks the queen for help
\rem /s1 Mordecai Asks for Esther's Help; Esther Agrees to Help the Jews; Esther plans to rescue the Jews; Mordecai Requests Esther's Help; Mordecai Persuades Esther to Help
\p
\v 1 When Mordekai found out about what had been done, he tore his clothesВҰ229874 and dressed in sackclothВҰ229876 and \add threw\add* ashesВҰ229877 \add over himself (as a sign of mourning or distress)\add* and wentВҰ229878 out into the cityВҰ229880 centre, wailing loudlyВҰ229883 and bitterlyВҰ229884.
\v 2 ButВҰ229886 no one was wearing mourning garb was allowed inside the king's gate, so when Mordekai reached the gate, he had to stay just outside it.
\v 3 In every provinceВҰ229904 of the empire, the letter that said to destroy the Jews was publicly displayed and when the Jews heard about itВҰ229921, they were incredibly upset. They skipped meals and wailed loudly, and many of them also wore sackclothВҰ229919 and threw ashesВҰ229920 on themselves and lay on the ground.
\p
\v 4 WhenВҰ229924 \add Queen\add* Esther'sВҰ229929 young female attendants cameВҰ229924 with her guardians andВҰ229924 told her \add what was going on outside\add*, even the queenВҰ229934 became very scared. She sentВҰ229936 Mordekai some good clothesВҰ229938 to wear instead of the sackclothВҰ229943, butВҰ229924 he wouldn't acceptВҰ229946 them.
\v 5 The kingВҰ229952 had assigned some of the royal guardians to Esther personally, so Esther calledВҰ229948 for one of themвҖ”a man named HathakВҰ229950. She told him to go out and speak with Mordekai and find out what he was so distressed about.
\v 6 SoВҰ229970 HathakВҰ229971 wentВҰ229970 out to \add talk to\add* MordekaiВҰ229974 who was out in the plaza in frontВҰ229980 of the king'sВҰ229983 gateВҰ229981.
\v 7 Mordekai told him everything thatВҰ229998 Haman was planning to do andВҰ229985 even told him how much moneyВҰ229997 Haman had said the king would get for his treasuriesВҰ230004 if \add the king commanded people\add* to kill all the Jews.
\v 8 Mordekai also gaveВҰ230022 Hathak a copy of the letter that the announcers had read out loud inВҰ230020 ShushanВҰ230020, that said that people must kill all the Jews. He told Hathak to show the letter to EstherВҰ230027 so that she would know exactly what it said and also told him to urge her to go to the kingВҰ230035 personally and to beg him desperately to save her people \add from destructionВҰ230021\add*.
\v 9 SoВҰ230045 HathakВҰ230046 returned to the queen andВҰ230047 told her what Mordekai had said,
\v 10 andВҰ230056 EstherВҰ230054 told himВҰ230056 to go back to Mordekai with this message:
\v 11 вҖңThere's a law about going to the king that applies to everyoneВҰ230071 in the kingdom, both men and women. If anyoneВҰ230089 goes into the innerВҰ230084 courtyardВҰ230083 of the palace, where the king can see them, and the king has not summoned them, that person will be executed. Only if the king holdsВҰ230094 out his golden scepterВҰ230100 to them, then they will live. (EveryoneВҰ230089 in the whole empire knows this law.) The king hasn't called for me in over a month\add , and if I go in without being summoned, I could be put to deathВҰ230091\add*.вҖқ
\p
\v 12 \add SoВҰ230117 Hathak\add* went back to Mordekai andВҰ230117 told him what the queen had said.
\v 13 Mordekai told \add Hathak\add* to tell this to EstherВҰ230129: вҖңDon't imagineВҰ230132 that just because you live there inВҰ230133 the king's palace that you'll be safe when they kill all the other Jews.
\v 14 If you say nothing atВҰ230147 all now, someone from some other placeВҰ230153 will rescue the Jews, butВҰ230150 you and your relatives will not survive. Who knows, perhaps it was for a time just like this that \add God allowed\add* you to become queen?вҖқ
\p
\v 15 ThenВҰ230169 EstherВҰ230170 sent this replyВҰ230171 to MordekaiВҰ230174:
\v 16 вҖңGo and assemble all the Jews who live here in ShushanВҰ230184, and tell them to fast and pray for my sakeвҖ”tell them to not eat or drinkВҰ230192 anything for three days and three nightsВҰ230195. My female attendants and I will also fast in the same way. At the end of the three days, I will go in to talk to the king even though it's against the law. I will do thatВҰ230208 even if it costs me my life.вҖқ
\p
\v 17 SoВҰ230216 MordekaiВҰ230217 wentВҰ230216 andВҰ230218 did everythingВҰ230219 that EstherВҰ230224 had told him to do.
\c 5
\s1 Esther goes to the king without an invitation
\rem /s1 Esther's Banquet; Esther Invites the King and Haman to a Banquet; Esther's Request to the King
\p
\v 1 Three days later, the \add Queen\add* EstherВҰ230232 put on her royal robesВҰ230231 and \add went and\add* stoodВҰ230234 in the innerВҰ230239 courtyardВҰ230235 of the palace, across from the king's house. He was in the royal palace, sittingВҰ230244 on the royal throneВҰ230247 and facing the room's entranceВҰ230252.
\v 2 As soon as the king noticedВҰ230256 Esther standingВҰ230262 there inВҰ230263 the courtyardВҰ230263, he was very pleased to see her. SoВҰ230255 he held out his golden scepter to her and Esther came up \add to the throne\add* and touchedВҰ230278 the top of the scepter.
\v 3 вҖңWhy have you come here, Queen EstherВҰ230289?вҖқ the kingВҰ230285 asked. вҖңWhat do you want? Tell me, and I'll give you anything you ask forвҖ”even half of the empire.вҖқ
\p
\v 4 вҖңIf it pleases your majesty,вҖқ EstherВҰ230302 replied, вҖңplease comeВҰ230309 with HamanВҰ230311 today to the banquetВҰ230315 thatВҰ230316 I'veВҰ230318 prepared for you.вҖқ
\p
\v 5 The king said to his servants, вҖң\add Go and\add* get HamanвҖқ the king told his servants, вҖңand bringВҰ230323 him quicklyВҰ230323 so that we can do what the queen has asked us.вҖқ SoВҰ230321 the king and Haman wentВҰ230332 to the banquetВҰ230337 that EstherВҰ230331 had had prepared for them.
\v 6 While they were drinkingВҰ230346 wine, the king said to EstherВҰ230345, вҖңNow please tell me what you \add really\add* want. I'll give you anything you ask for, no matter how much it is. I truly mean what I am saying.вҖқ
\p
\v 7 вҖңThis is what I \add really\add* want.вҖқ EstherВҰ230363 replied.
\v 8 вҖңYour majesty, if you're pleased with me and if you're happy to give me what I want, please comeВҰ230388 with HamanВҰ230390 to \add another\add* banquetВҰ230393 thatВҰ230394 I'll prepare for you tomorrowВҰ230397 and I'll answer your question then.вҖқ
\s1 Haman's anger with Mordekai and his execution plan
\rem /s1 Haman Plots to Kill Mordecai; Haman's Plan to Kill Mordecai; Haman Plans to Have Mordecai Hanged; Haman's Rage Against Mordecai
\p
\v 9 Haman was feeling very happy as he left \add the banquet\add* that dayВҰ230404. ButВҰ230402 thenВҰ230402 he sawВҰ230409 Mordekai sitting atВҰ230414 the king's gateВҰ230414 andВҰ230402 noticedВҰ230409 that Mordekai didn'tВҰ230416 stand up or show fearful reverence to him. This made Haman furious withВҰ230414 Mordekai
\v 10 butВҰ230430 he restrained himself and wentВҰ230432 homeВҰ230435. ThenВҰ230430 he sentВҰ230436 for his friendsВҰ230440 and broughtВҰ230437 in his wife, ZereshВҰ230443,
\v 11 boasting to them about how rich he was and about how many sons he had, and how the king had promotedВҰ230463 him \add many times\add* and given him a position aboveВҰ230464 all of the other officialsВҰ230466 and administrators.
\v 12 вҖңAnd that is not all,вҖқ HamanВҰ230471 added. вҖңI was the only one that Queen EstherВҰ230476 invited to go with the king to a banquetВҰ230483 that she preparedВҰ230486 for us today. And she's also invited only me to go with the king again tomorrowВҰ230493.
\v 13 However, I still can't be happy as long as I keep seeingВҰ230513 that Jew, Mordekai, sittingВҰ230518 there atВҰ230519 the king'sВҰ230520 gateВҰ230519.вҖқ
\p
\v 14 Then ZereshВҰ230524 his wife and all his friendsВҰ230528 said to him, вҖңGet them to install 25-metre high pole, and inВҰ230535 the morningВҰ230535 get permission from the king, and get them to impale Mordekai onВҰ230535 it. Then you can go withВҰ230535 the king to the banquetВҰ230553 and enjoy yourself.вҖқ
\p That idea sounded good to HamanВҰ230558, so he got the pole erected.
\c 6
\s1 The king honours Mordekai
\rem /s1 Haman executed; The King Honours Mordecai; Mordecai Honoured
\p
\v 1 ThatВҰ230570 nightВҰ230563 the king was unable to sleepВҰ230566 so he ordered the royal recordsВҰ230573 to be fetched and to be read to him.
\v 2 The recordsВҰ230582 mentioned that BigthanВҰ230588 andВҰ230581 TereshВҰ230589, two of the royal guardiansВҰ230593 who protected the doorway to the king's private quarters, had planned to assassinate the king, butВҰ230581 that Mordekai had reported it.
\v 3 вҖңWhat honourВҰ230607 or recognition did I give Mordekai for saving my life?вҖқ the king asked.
\p вҖңNothing was done for him,вҖқ replied the youngВҰ230614 men who were attendingВҰ230616 him.
\p
\v 4 At that moment, HamanВҰ230627 had entered the outerВҰ230633 courtyard of the king's houseВҰ230630. He had come to tell the king that he wanted to execute Mordekai onВҰ230626 the pole that he'd had set up for him.
\p вҖңWho's out inВҰ230626 the courtyard?вҖқ the king asked.
\p
\v 5 вҖңHaman'sВҰ230653 out thereВҰ230652 standingВҰ230654 in the courtyardВҰ230655,вҖқ replied the young men.
\p вҖңBring him in thenВҰ230648,вҖқ the king instructed.
\p
\v 6 WhenВҰ230660 Haman came inВҰ230668, the king asked him, вҖңWhat should I do for a man that I would really like to honour?вҖқ
\p Haman thought to himself, вҖңSurely it must be me that the king would like to honour more than anyone else?вҖқ
\v 7 so he replied to the king, вҖңIfВҰ230685 you really want to honourВҰ230693 someone,
\v 8 tell your servants to bring one of your own royal robes that you have already worn yourself and also bring a horseВҰ230703 that you have already riddenВҰ230705 yourself and put a royal crown onВҰ230712 its head.
\v 9 ThenВҰ230714 have one of your most nobleВҰ230724 officialsВҰ230722 present the man withВҰ230732 the robe and the horse. Have your servants put the robe on the man whom you really want to honour and have them seat that man on the horse and thenВҰ230714 lead the horse through the public squareВҰ230737 of the cityВҰ230738 while they shout out \add to everyone\add* inВҰ230732 front of them, вҖҳThe king is doing this because he really wants to honour this man!вҖҷ вҖқ
\p
\v 10 The king \add agreed so\add* he replied to HamanВҰ230751, вҖңGo quickly and take the robe and the horseВҰ230759 and do what you've just described for Mordekai the Jew who sits by the gateВҰ230768 to the palace. Make sure that you do absolutely everything that you've said.вҖқ
\p
\v 11 SoВҰ230778 HamanВҰ230779 got the robe and the horse and put the robe on Mordekai, seated him on the horse, and thenВҰ230778 led the horse through the public squareВҰ230791 of the cityВҰ230792. As he did, he shouted out to everyone inВҰ230791 front of him, вҖңThe king is doing this because he really wants to honourВҰ230801 this man!вҖқ
\p
\v 12 Afterwards, Mordekai returnedВҰ230803 to the king's gateВҰ230807 butВҰ230803 HamanВҰ230809 hurriedВҰ230810 to his house, coveringВҰ230815 his head like a mournerВҰ230814.
\v 13 \add At home\add* he explained to Zeresh his wife and to all his friendsВҰ230824 everything that had happenedВҰ230829 to him. ThenВҰ230818 his advisorsВҰ230833 and his wife saidВҰ230830 to him, вҖңMordekai has begunВҰ230841 to defeat you and since he is one of the JewishВҰ230838 peopleВҰ230837, you won'tВҰ230844 win against himвҖ”instead, he'll certainlyВҰ230850 defeat you.вҖқ
\s1 Haman's execution
\rem /s1 Haman Is Put to Death; Haman's Downfall and Mordecai's Advancement
\p
\v 14 While they were still talkingВҰ230855 together, \add some of\add* the royal guardians arrivedВҰ230859 to bringВҰ230861 HamanВҰ230864 quickly to the banquetВҰ230867 thatВҰ230868 EstherВҰ230871 had had preparedВҰ230870.
\c 7
\rem /s1 The King Executes Haman; Haman Hanged
\p
\v 1 SoВҰ230873 the kingВҰ230874 andВҰ230875 HamanВҰ230875 wentВҰ230873 to Queen Esther'sВҰ230879 \add banquet\add*.
\v 2 While they were drinkingВҰ230888 wine atВҰ230888 that secondВҰ230887 banquet, the king asked Esther again, вҖңNow please tell me what you really want, Queen Esther. Tell me, andВҰ230882 I'll do it for youвҖ”I'll give you anything you ask for, no matter what it is.вҖқ
\p
\v 3 вҖңYour majesty,вҖқ Queen EstherВҰ230907 replied, вҖңif you are pleased withВҰ230914 me, I hope you'll be willing to do what I ask. Please allow me to live, andВҰ230906 please save my peopleВҰ230927. That is what I am asking for
\v 4 because someone has turned me and my peopleВҰ230933 over \add to our enemies\add* and they're going to completely destroyВҰ230934 us. If someone had \add just\add* sold the men and even the women to be slaves, I wouldn't have said anything, because that wouldn't have been important enough to bother your majesty withВҰ230946.вҖқ
\p
\v 5 вҖңWho has done this?вҖқ KingВҰ230951 AhasuerusВҰ230952 asked her. вҖңWhere is the man who has dared to do such a thing?вҖқ
\p
\v 6 вҖңThe man who is our bitter enemyВҰ230975 is this evil man Haman!вҖқ answered EstherВҰ230972.
\p \add By this time,\add* Haman was terrifiedВҰ230980 standing there in front of the kingВҰ230982 andВҰ230970 the queenВҰ230983.
\v 7 Now the king became so angry that he got up and abandoned his wine-drinking atВҰ230987 the banquet and went outside into the palaceВҰ230993 gardenВҰ230992. ButВҰ230985 HamanВҰ230994 stayed inside to beg his life from Queen EstherВҰ231000 because he recognized that the king wanted to \add execute\add* him.
\v 8 \add As he was pleading for his life,\add* Haman \add knelt down\add* very close to EstherВҰ231028 as she was \add reclining\add* onВҰ231038 a couchВҰ231026. WhenВҰ231012 the king returnedВҰ231013 from the palaceВҰ231015 gardenВҰ231014 to the room where they had been drinking wine, he \add saw this and\add* exclaimed, вҖң\add Now\add* he's even trying to rape the queenВҰ231036 in my presence and in my own houseВҰ231018!вҖқ
\p As soon as the king said this, some of his servants coveredВҰ231045 Haman's faceВҰ231043 \add (as a sign thatВҰ231027 he would be executed)\add*.
\v 9 Then HarbonaВҰ231049, who was one of the guardians who served the king personally, said, вҖңYour majesty, Haman has also set up a pole twenty-five metres high at his houseВҰ231073 because he wants to hang Mordekai on it. ButВҰ231048 Mordekai saved your life.вҖқ
\p вҖңExecute Haman on it!вҖқ the king commanded.
\p
\v 10 SoВҰ231083 they impaled HamanВҰ231086 on the pole thatВҰ231090 he had set up for MordekaiВҰ231093, andВҰ231083 thenВҰ231083 the king's angerВҰ231094 dissipated.
\c 8
\s1 The Jews are enabled to defend themselves
\rem /s1 Esther Saves the Jews; The King's Edict in Behalf of the Jews; A Decree to Help the Jews; The Jews Are Told to Fight Back
\p
\v 1 That same dayВҰ231099, KingВҰ231102 AhasuerusВҰ231103 gave Queen Esther all the property that had belonged to HamanВҰ231109, the enemy of the Jews. Esther told the king that Mordekai was \add her cousin and that he had been like a father\add* to her, and \add so the king summoned\add* Mordekai to come to him.
\v 2 ThenВҰ231126 the kingВҰ231127 removed his signetВҰ231130 ring whichВҰ231131 he had retrieved from Haman, andВҰ231126 gaveВҰ231134 it to Mordekai. The queen also put Mordekai in charge of all the property thatВҰ231131 had belonged to Haman.
\rem /s1 The triumphant Jews destroy their enemies
\p
\v 3 Then EstherВҰ231148 came to speak to the king againВҰ231147, and she knelt down and put her face right on top of his feet. She cried as she begged him to stop Haman'sВҰ231163 terrible plan to destroy the Jews.
\v 4 TheВҰ231180 king held out his golden scepterВҰ231177 toward EstherВҰ231175, so she stoodВҰ231181 up andВҰ231173 waited facing the king.
\v 5 вҖңYour majesty,вҖқ she saidВҰ231185, вҖңif you think that it's the rightВҰ231197 thing to do, andВҰ231192 if you're pleased withВҰ231203 me, please write a new letter revokingВҰ231205 the lettersВҰ231208 that HamanВҰ231210 (the son of HammedathaВҰ231213, the AgagiteВҰ231214) sent out \add instructing the people\add* to destroyВҰ231217 all the Jews throughout your empire.
\v 6 I couldn't bear to see the terrible thing thatВҰ231232 is about to happen to my peopleВҰ231237. I \add certainly\add* couldn't bear to see \add all\add* my relatives destroyedВҰ231241!вҖқ
\p
\v 7 Then kingВҰ231246 AhasuerusВҰ231247 saidВҰ231245 to Queen Esther and to Mordekai the Jew, вҖңListen, I'veВҰ231256 givenВҰ231256 the houseВҰ231253 of HamanВҰ231255 to Esther, and they've executed him onВҰ231268 the pole because he attempted to destroy the Jews.
\v 8 ButВҰ231271 as you \add both\add* know, no one can revokeВҰ231296 a letter thatВҰ231286 has my name and my official seal on it. SoВҰ231271 this is what you should do: writeВҰ231272 \add a new letter\add* to help the JewsВҰ231275, as you think best and put my name on it and seal the letter withВҰ231277 my signet ring.вҖқ
\p
\v 9 It was now June, and the kingВҰ231301 sent for his scribes and they wrote a letter to the Jews containing everything thatВҰ231330 Mordekai dictated. It was also addressed to royal officialsВҰ231328, and to the governorsВҰ231327 and leaders in each province. The empire had 127 provinces, extending all the way from IndiaВҰ231332 \add in the east\add* to EthiopiaВҰ231335 \add in the west\add*. The scribes wrote to every province using its own alphabet and to each people group in its own language, and to the Jews in their language and using their alphabet.
\v 10 The letters were written inВҰ231357 KingВҰ231354 Ahasuerus' name, andВҰ231352 \add each one\add* was sealedВҰ231356 withВҰ231357 the king's signetВҰ231357 ring. ThenВҰ231352 the letters were distributed by mountedВҰ231363 couriersВҰ231362 riding onВҰ231357 swift horsesВҰ231365 bred from the royalВҰ231366 mares.
\p
\v 11 The letters stated that the king permittedВҰ231371 the Jews in each and everyВҰ231391 city to get together and defendВҰ231382 themselves, and what's more to destroyВҰ231386, killВҰ231386, and annihilateВҰ231388 all the forces of any peopleВҰ231394 or provinceВҰ231395 hostile to them, including womenВҰ231399 and children, and \add then\add* to plunderВҰ231401 their possessions.
\v 12 \add This was to take place\add* on a certain day inВҰ231410 every provinceВҰ231407 throughout the empire: the 13th of March\x + \xo 8:12: \xt 3:7.\x* \add (the same day on which Haman's law was to take effect)\add*.
\v 13 A copy of the decree was to be included as law in every provinceВҰ231427 and to be displayedВҰ231429 to all the peopleВҰ231432 so that the Jews could be prepared to fight back against theirВҰ231441 enemiesВҰ231441 on that dayВҰ231438.
\v 14 So the couriersВҰ231443 onВҰ231450 the royalВҰ231446 horsesВҰ231445 rode out quickly under the king's orders to deliver the letters. The new law was also proclaimed throughout the capital city of ShushanВҰ231454.
\p
\v 15 The kingВҰ231462 \add gave\add* Mordekai royalВҰ231464 clothing that was blue and whiteВҰ231466, withВҰ231463 a large goldВҰ231468 crownВҰ231467, and a purpleВҰ231472 robeВҰ231470 made from fine linenВҰ231471. The people of ShushanВҰ231474 cheered happily when Mordekai exited \add the palace\add*.
\v 16 For the Jews, itВҰ231479 was \add a time\add* of lightВҰ231480 and happiness, and they were honoured \add by those around them\add*.
\v 17 In every single provinceВҰ231487 and in every single city, whereverВҰ231494 the letter announcing the king's decree was brought, the Jews were very cheerfulВҰ231501 and had big celebrations. Many peopleВҰ231507 from other groups in the empire became afraid of the Jews, so they \add converted to Judaism\add* themselves.
\c 9
\s1 The Jews destroy their enemies
\rem /s1 The Jews Destroy Their Enemies; Triumph of the Jews; The Victory of the Jews; Destruction of the Enemies of the Jews
\p
\v 1 \add Finally\add* when the 13th of March arrived, it was time for everyone to do what the letters from the king said that he had decreed for them to do. The enemies of the Jews had expected to destroy the Jews onВҰ231518 that day butВҰ231518 just the opposite happenedвҖ”instead, it was the Jews who destroyed theirВҰ231549 enemies.
\v 2 Throughout the empire, the Jews joined together in theirВҰ231571 citiesВҰ231553 to defend themselves against those who wanted to harm them. No one was able to fight back against them because everyoneВҰ231563 \add else\add* in the empire had become afraid of them.
\v 3 All the leaders in each provinceВҰ231581, the royal officialsВҰ231580, the governorsВҰ231583, andВҰ231578 everyone who worked for the kingВҰ231587 helped the Jews because they had become afraid of Mordekai
\v 4 because he was \add now\add* a very important royal official, and his fame spread throughout the provincesВҰ231610 as he became more and more powerfulВҰ231616.
\v 5 So the Jews took their weapons and fought against all of their enemies and completely destroyedВҰ231628 them. They were able to do everything that theyВҰ231631 wanted to do against their enemies.
\p
\v 6 In the capital city of Shushan, the Jews killedВҰ231635 500 men
\v 7 including \add Haman's ten sons\add* ParshandathaВҰ231644, DalphonВҰ231647, AspathaВҰ231650,
\v 8 PorathaВҰ231654, AdaliaВҰ231657, AridathaВҰ231660,
\v 9 ParmashtaВҰ231664, ArisaiВҰ231667, AridaiВҰ231670, andВҰ231662 VaizathaВҰ231673.
\v 10 Those were the tenВҰ231675 sonsВҰ231676 of HamanВҰ231677 (son of HammedathaВҰ231680), the enemy of the Jews, butВҰ231684 the Jews didn'tВҰ231685 take theirВҰ231689 possessions.
\p
\v 11 At the end of the dayВҰ231691, the kingВҰ231699 received a report about how many people the Jews had killedВҰ231695 inВҰ231696 the capital city of ShushanВҰ231696
\v 12 and he told Queen EstherВҰ231704, вҖңHere inВҰ231706 the capital city of ShushanВҰ231706 the Jews have killed 500 men, including Haman'sВҰ231718 ten sonsВҰ231716. In the rest of my empire, they must have killed many more than that! So tell me what else you want and I'll do it for you. I'll do whatever you ask, so do tell me.вҖқ
\p
\v 13 вҖңIf it seems like a goodВҰ231742 plan to you, your majesty,вҖқ EstherВҰ231736 replied, вҖңthenВҰ231735 please allow the Jews who live here inВҰ231749 ShushanВҰ231749 to do again tomorrowВҰ231746 what you allowed them to do today. Also, command that the bodies of Haman'sВҰ231757 tenВҰ231754 sonsВҰ231755 be impaled onВҰ231749 the wooden pole.вҖқ
\v 14 ThenВҰ231763 the kingВҰ231764 ordered for this to be done and a decree was made throughout inВҰ231769 ShushanВҰ231769, and they \add publicly\add* impaled \add the bodies of \add* Haman'sВҰ231774 tenВҰ231771 sonsВҰ231772.
\v 15 SoВҰ231777 the next dayВҰ231784 onВҰ231782 the 14th, the Jews in Shushan gatheredВҰ231777 together again andВҰ231777 killedВҰ231789 300 \add more\add* men in Shushan. ButВҰ231777 \add once again\add* theyВҰ231796 did not take the things that belonged to those men.
\p
\v 16 The Jews inВҰ231804 the other parts of the empire, who had gathered together to fight for their livesВҰ231811 had defeated their enemies andВҰ231801 killedВҰ231814 75,000 of them. ButВҰ231801 they \add too\add* did not take the things that had belonged to their enemies.
\v 17 ThatВҰ231831 all happened on the 13th \add (as the law had said)\add*, and then they stopped on the 14th and made it a day of feastingВҰ231839 and celebration.
\rem /s1 Purim Celebrated; The Feast of Purim Inaugurated
\v 18 ButВҰ231842 the Jews inВҰ231846 ShushanВҰ231846 had gathered together \add and fought their enemies\add* on both the 13th and the 14th, so they stopped on the 15th and made it a dayВҰ231860 of feastingВҰ231861 and celebration.
\v 19 So that's why the Jews who liveВҰ231870 inВҰ231871 the ruralВҰ231872 villages observeВҰ231873 this holiday onВҰ231871 the 14th rather than the 15th. They celebrate withВҰ231871 feastingВҰ231881 and by giving gifts to each other.
\s1 The celebration named вҖҳPurimвҖҷ
\rem /s1 The Festival of Purim; The feast of Purim
\p
\v 20 Now Mordekai recordedВҰ231890 everything that had happened and sentВҰ231896 lettersВҰ231897 to all the Jews throughout the empire, in both the near provincesВҰ231906 and the far away ones.
\v 21 That decree established an annual holiday on the 14th and 15th of March every year,\f + \fr 9:21 \ft The OET-RV gives an approximate time of the year in our calendars, but the Jewish calendar is largely a lunar calendar so the dates of the feast in our calendars moves around a little. In 2024 for example, вҖҳPurimвҖҷ begins on the evening of March 23 in Yisrael/Israel and concludes at sundown on March 24.\f*
\v 22 because those were the days when the Jews no longer \add had to oppose\add* their enemiesВҰ231939 and that was the monthВҰ231940 when their sorrowВҰ231944 and mourningВҰ231946 had changedВҰ231942 into a good day. Now they were instructed to make them days of feastingВҰ231952 and happiness, and sendingВҰ231954 of giftsВҰ231958вҖ”to each other butВҰ231940 also to the needy.
\v 23 The Jews had already celebrated those days thatВҰ231964 way, so theyВҰ231966 \add readily\add* agreed to do what Mordekai had writtenВҰ231971.
\p
\v 24 Yes, HamanВҰ231976 (the son of HammedathaВҰ231979, the AgagiteВҰ231980), the enemy of all the Jews, had plotted to annihilate them, and he had thrownВҰ231990 a вҖҳPurвҖҷ (which is вҖҳlotвҖҷ or perhaps вҖҳdiceвҖҷ) \add choose the date\add* to crushВҰ231994 them and to destroy them.
\v 25 ButВҰ231997 \add instead they would remember how Queen Esther stood\add* in frontВҰ231998 of the kingВҰ231999, and how he had saidВҰ232000 in the letter, вҖңLet his evilВҰ232006 plot thatВҰ232007 he plotted concerning the Jews returnВҰ232004 on his head, and let them execute him and his sonsВҰ232020 on the pole.вҖқ
\v 26 Therefore they calledВҰ232028 this celebration вҖҳPurimВҰ232031вҖҷ\f + \fr 9:26 \ft Plural of Hebrew вҖҳPurвҖҷ meaning вҖҳlot/diceвҖҷ.\f* because of what they had experienced and because of the contents of \add Mordekai's\add* letterВҰ232044.
\v 27 The Jews agreed to establish those two days as holidays and to observeВҰ232075 them on those specific days as they'd been instructed. They agreed that they and theirВҰ232066 descendantsВҰ232066 and everyone who became part of the Jewish people would celebrate it every year.
\v 28 SoВҰ232087 that's why every Jewish familyВҰ232096 in every generationВҰ232093 \add since\add* has celebrated these days as holidays, wherever they live. The Jewish community andВҰ232087 its descendantsВҰ232112 will always faithfully observe this festival of вҖҳPurimвҖҷ.
\p
\v 29 Then Queen EstherВҰ232116 (the daughterВҰ232118 of AbihailВҰ232120), with \add help from\add* Mordekai the Jew, wroteВҰ232115 a secondВҰ232133 letterВҰ232130 about вҖҳPurimвҖҷ.
\v 30 He sentВҰ232135 this \add second \add* letterВҰ232136 to all the Jews throughout the empire of King AhasuerusВҰ232149, with wordsВҰ232150 of peaceВҰ232151 andВҰ232145 truthВҰ232152
\v 31 to set up the вҖҳPurimвҖҷ celebration onВҰ232160 the given dates according to what Mordekai the Jew and Queen EstherВҰ232166 had determined for them. \add They also confirmed\add* that the Jews should continue the timesВҰ232160 of fastingВҰ232177 and mourning that theyВҰ232169 had establishedВҰ232154 for themselves and theirВҰ232172 future descendantsВҰ232175.
\v 32 SoВҰ232180 Esther'sВҰ232181 decree confirmedВҰ232182 theseВҰ232185 regulations about вҖҳPurimвҖҷ andВҰ232180 they were writtenВҰ232186 into the \add official\add* record.
\c 10
\s1 The grandeur of King Ahasuerus and Mordekai
\rem /s1 The Greatness of Mordecai; The Greatness of Xerxes and Mordecai
\p
\v 1 Then KingВҰ232191 AhasuerusВҰ232192 imposed a taxВҰ232195 \add on everyone\add* throughout his empire, including \add those\add* on the islandsВҰ232199 of the \add Mediterranean\add* Sea.
\v 2 Everything he accomplished through his powerВҰ232205 and strength is writtenВҰ232216 down in the \add royal\add* records of the kingsВҰ232222 of MediaВҰ232223 and PersiaВҰ232224, as well as the complete accountВҰ232207 of the high position to which the kingВҰ232212 promoted Mordekai.
\v 3 Mordekai the Jew was second-in-commandВҰ232230 to the king AhasuerusВҰ232232, and a leader amongВҰ232234 the Jews. He was popularВҰ232235 with most of his own peopleВҰ232240, seekingВҰ232238 good for them and teaching all his descendants \add how to live in\add* peaceВҰ232242.
